{
  "text": "The recognition and binding of NF-\u03baB complexes to target DNA are not sufficient for full gene transcription. A vast array of coregulators, including coactivators and corepressors, have been implicated to play a crucial role in nuclear NF-\u03baB signaling, most of which physically associate with Rel subunits. Recent work on the astrocyte elevated gene-1 (AEG-1) [CITATION_1] and the inhibitor of growth 4 (ING4) [CITATION_2] in malignant glioma has further expanded this extensive list. AEG-1 is not found within the nucleus; however, on TNF\u03b1 treatment, it translocates into the nucleus and associates with p65. AEG-1 was also observed to interact with CBP and complex at the promoter of IL-8 gene, thus functioning as a coactivator to bridge NF-\u03baB, CBP, and basal transcription machinery [CITATION_3] . In contrast, ING4 was recently identified as a corepressor of NF-\u03baB transactivation. It is recruited to the \u03baB promoters simultaneously with NF-\u03baB, which correlates with reductions in p65 phosphorylation, p300 recruitment, and the levels of acetylated histones, but enhances the levels of HDAC-1 at these promoters [CITATION_4] . Thus, ING4 negatively regulates the activity of the NF-\u03baB bound to target gene promoters through its specific interaction with p65 [CITATION_5] .",
